findingsText:
 The research has identified (1) the distinctive actions of a novel chemical on the human versus non-human P2X7 receptors; (2) the molecular mechanism by which disease-associated mutations in the human P2X7 receptors alter the receptor function; (3) the molecular basis underpinning the inhibitory of actions by trace metal ions on the P2X7 receptors. (1) The novel chemical has been widely used since as the human P2X7 antagonists in preclinical studies of the physiological and pathological functions of the P2X7 receptors; 
(2) the molecular mechanisms by which disease-associated mutations alter the P2X7 receptor have been used to better understand how the causative relationships of mutations and diseases;
(3) the identification of the molecular basis of the inhibition by trace mental ions provides a better understanding of how they modulate the receptor-mediated functions. Healthcare,Manufacturing, including Industrial Biotechology,Pharmaceuticals and Medical Biotechnology
